		{"id":"a15e72f5c5ba0c72","type":"text","text":"# Task CD-T01 ‚Äì Draft Servo Control Block Diagram\n\nHere is a **block diagram** representing a **full servo control architecture for the puppet system**, suitable for moving into schematic design and firmware mapping. This version assumes a moderately complex puppet with:\n\n- Multiple servo channels\n    \n- Input triggers (manual or sensor-based)\n    \n- Audio synchronization for mouth/gesture\n    \n- Power distribution with protection\n    \n\n---\n\n### üß† **High-Level Block Diagram: Puppet Servo Control Architecture**\n\n```mermaid\nflowchart LR\n  %% Core Controller\n  MCU[Microcontroller Unit]\n\n  %% Input Section\n  TRIG[Input Triggers - Buttons and Sensors]\n  AUDIO[Audio Input or Player]\n  SYNC[Audio Sync Decoder - Envelope Detector]\n\n  %% Power System\n  VIN[Power Source - LiPo or DC]\n  PROTECT[Protection - Fuse or TVS]\n  REG[Voltage Regulator or BEC]\n\n  %% Servo Channels\n  CH1[Servo Channel 1]\n  CH2[Servo Channel 2]\n  CH3[Servo Channel 3]\n  CHN[Servo Channel N]\n\n  %% Connections\n  VIN --> PROTECT --> REG\n  REG --> MCU\n\n  TRIG --> MCU\n  AUDIO --> SYNC --> MCU\n\n  MCU --> CH1\n  MCU --> CH2\n  MCU --> CH3\n  MCU --> CHN\n\n  REG --> CH1\n  REG --> CH2\n  REG --> CH3\n  REG --> CHN\n\n```\n\n---\n\n### üîß **Key Functional Areas**\n\n| Block                          | Description                                                                                          |\n| ------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **MCU (Microcontroller Unit)** | Central logic; runs firmware, PWM/PPM generation for servos, interprets triggers and audio sync      |\n| **Input Triggers**             | Manual switches, buttons, capacitive touch sensors, IR, ultrasonic, or motion sensors                |\n| **Audio Input**                | Audio playback module (DFPlayer, I2S DAC, or line-in from external source)                           |\n| **Audio Sync Decoder**         | Processes audio signals into envelope data or phoneme events for lip-sync or gesture sync            |\n| **Power Management**           | Regulates system voltage (e.g. 7.4V LiPo ‚Üí 5V/6V BEC for servos, 3.3V for logic); includes filtering |\n| **Protection**                 | Surge, ESD, or overcurrent protection upstream of regulators                                         |\n| **Servo Channels**             | PWM outputs directly controlling servo motors; each gets power and signal                            |\n\n---\n\n### üìå Optional Extensions\n\n- **I2C/SPI Expansion Modules**: For extending input/output without using more MCU pins\n    \n- **Wireless Control Layer**: BLE or RF modules for remote input\n    \n- **Feedback Loops**: Potentiometers or IMUs for joint angle feedback (future refinement)\n    \n\nWould you like this exported as a PNG or PDF version for documentation, or embedded into a project datasheet in Obsidian/Markdown format?","x":80,"y":1700,"width":1545,"height":1712},
		{"id":"3042524fdee7ae06","type":"text","text":"# Task CD-T02 ‚Äì Design Schematic in CAD Software\n\nTo translate the approved block diagram into a **formal schematic** using electrical CAD (e.g., KiCad, Eagle, Altium), here‚Äôs a **step-by-step breakdown** of how the schematic should be structured to follow best practices in layout, net labeling, and future PCB design.\n\n---\n\n## ‚úÖ **Formal Schematic Structure for Puppet Servo Control System**\n\n### üìê 1. **Schematic Sheet Organization**\n\nUse **sheet blocks or hierarchical pages** if needed:\n\n- Page 1: Power Input & Regulation\n    \n- Page 2: MCU Core & Programming Interface\n    \n- Page 3: Servo Output Channels\n    \n- Page 4: Audio & Trigger Inputs\n    \n\n---\n\n### üîå 2. **Power Regulation Block**\n\n**Components:**\n\n- Input connector (e.g., JST or barrel jack)\n    \n- TVS diode for surge protection\n    \n- Fuse or PTC resettable fuse\n    \n- Buck or LDO regulator (e.g., AMS1117-5V or switching BEC module)\n    \n- Decoupling capacitors (0.1¬µF, 10¬µF)\n    \n\n**Nets:**\n\n- `VIN`\n    \n- `VREG_5V` (to servos)\n    \n- `VCC_3V3` or `VCC_MCU` (logic supply for MCU)\n    \n- `GND`\n    \n\n---\n\n### üß† 3. **MCU Core & Programming Header**\n\n**Components:**\n\n- MCU (e.g., ATmega328P, STM32, ESP32, etc.)\n    \n- Decoupling caps close to VCC/GND\n    \n- Reset pull-up + push button\n    \n- Crystal oscillator and load caps (if needed)\n    \n- Programming/debug header (e.g., SWD, ICSP, or USB-to-UART)\n    \n\n**Nets:**\n\n- `VCC_MCU`, `GND`\n    \n- `RESET`, `TX`, `RX`, `SWDIO`, `SWCLK`\n    \n- Servo PWM output lines: `PWM_CH1`, `PWM_CH2`, ..., `PWM_CHN`\n    \n\n---\n\n### üîÑ 4. **Servo Headers (Output Block)**\n\n**Components:**\n\n- Multiple 3-pin headers (Signal + VREG_5V + GND)\n    \n- Optional: series resistors (100Œ©) on signal lines for damping\n    \n\n**Label each servo net clearly:**\n\n- `PWM_CH1`, `PWM_CH2`, `PWM_CH3`, ... `PWM_CHN`\n    \n\n**Example:**\n\n```\n[Pin 1] PWM_CH1\n[Pin 2] VREG_5V\n[Pin 3] GND\n```\n\n---\n\n### üé§ 5. **Audio Input & Sync Decoder**\n\n**Options:**\n\n- Line-in jack or onboard audio module (e.g., DFPlayer Mini)\n    \n- Audio envelope follower (e.g., op-amp + diode-based peak detector)\n    \n- Analog output to MCU: `AUDIO_ENV`\n    \n- Optional: I2C audio processor\n    \n\n**Nets:**\n\n- `AUDIO_IN`\n    \n- `AUDIO_ENV` ‚Üí connect to MCU analog pin (e.g., `A0`)\n    \n\n---\n\n### üß≤ 6. **Trigger Input Block**\n\n**Components:**\n\n- Mechanical buttons, capacitive sensors, IR, etc.\n    \n- Pull-down resistors (10k) or internal pull-ups in MCU\n    \n- Signal lines debounced in firmware or with RC filters\n    \n\n**Nets:**\n\n- `TRIG_1`, `TRIG_2`, etc. ‚Üí connect to digital I/O\n    \n\n---\n\n### üß∞ 7. **Labeling & Best Practices**\n\n**Follow these conventions:**\n\n- Use consistent prefixes (`VCC_`, `PWM_`, `TRIG_`)\n    \n- Place **net labels** on all connected traces instead of chaining long wires\n    \n- Separate **power planes** in PCB later (don‚Äôt route servo power through MCU)\n    \n- Group related blocks with bounding boxes and titles\n    \n\n---\n\n### üìé 8. **Recommended Toolchain File Output**\n\nIf you're using **KiCad**, the final deliverables would include:\n\n- `.sch` schematic file\n    \n- Netlist or `.kicad_pcb` ready for layout\n    \n- BOM with:\n    \n    - MCU part number\n        \n    - Regulator IC\n        \n    - TVS diode\n        \n    - Headers\n        \n    - Audio module/sync components\n        \n\n---\n\n### üß± Schematic Block Summary\n\n|Block|Key Components|Output Nets|\n|---|---|---|\n|Power In|DC jack, TVS, fuse, buck|VIN, VREG_5V, VCC_MCU|\n|MCU Core|MCU, decoupling, reset, crystal|PWM, TRIG, AUDIO_ENV|\n|Servo Outputs|Header x N|PWM_CH1..CHN|\n|Audio Sync|Line-in or module, envelope follower|AUDIO_ENV|\n|Triggers|Buttons/sensors + pull-downs|TRIG_1..N|\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to generate:\n\n- A KiCad project with `.sch` files?\n    \n- A visual schematic PDF?\n    \n- A parts list (BOM) in CSV format?","x":1720,"y":1700,"width":1240,"height":3820},
		{"id":"0f6862c3477afb7f","type":"text","text":"# Task CD-T03 ‚Äì Perform ERC and Net Validation\n\nTo conduct a complete **Electrical Rule Check (ERC)** and **netlist validation** of your schematic (as described for **CD-T02**), follow this professional verification process. This walkthrough assumes you are using **KiCad**, **Eagle**, or a comparable ECAD tool:\n\n---\n\n## ‚úÖ **Step-by-Step: Electrical Rule Check (ERC) and Netlist Validation**\n\n### üß™ 1. **ERC: Electrical Rule Check**\n\nRun ERC to validate the logical structure and connectivity of your schematic. Focus areas:\n\n#### ‚úÖ Common Checks\n\n|Issue|Description|Resolution|\n|---|---|---|\n|**Unconnected Pins**|Pins not tied to any net|Add missing connections or terminate unused I/O with NC (No Connect) flags|\n|**Floating Power Inputs**|Power pins (e.g., VCC, GND) left unconnected or missing power flags|Use \"Power Flag\" symbols on all power inputs (especially regulators, MCUs)|\n|**Conflicting Pin Types**|Output driving output or input left floating|Insert buffers, tri-states, or correct schematic logic|\n|**No GND Reference**|GND net not consistently connected|Ensure all GND symbols tie into one GND net|\n|**Mixed Voltage Domains**|5V signals interfacing 3.3V logic|Add level shifters where needed|\n\n> üõ†Ô∏è In **KiCad**, click: **Inspect > Electrical Rules Checker**, and resolve each issue in the \"Violations\" panel.\n\n---\n\n### üßµ 2. **Net Label Validation**\n\nEnsure **net labels** are:\n\n- Unique and meaningful: `PWM_CH1`, `TRIG_1`, `AUDIO_ENV`, `VREG_5V`\n    \n- Properly assigned at both ends of connection (source & sink)\n    \n- Free from typos or redundant labels\n    \n\n#### üßπ Clean Up Practices:\n\n- Remove unnamed nets unless deliberately floating (then mark NC)\n    \n- Prefer named nets to visual wires for clarity in layout\n    \n- Use `global` net labels for inter-sheet connectivity (if using hierarchical sheets)\n    \n\n---\n\n### üìé 3. **ERC Pin Type Table Cross-Check**\n\nCheck your schematic symbols are correctly typed:\n\n|Symbol Pin Type|Valid Connection To|\n|---|---|\n|Output|Input, Bidirectional|\n|Open Collector|Pull-up Resistor, Input|\n|Passive|Passive, Power|\n|Power Input|Power Output, Power Flag|\n|Power Output|Power Input only|\n|Tri-state|Tri-state control logic|\n\nYou can correct pin types in your symbol editor if necessary.\n\n---\n\n### üß¨ 4. **Netlist Generation and Validation**\n\nNow generate the **netlist** and confirm that all connections are mapped correctly.\n\n#### In KiCad:\n\n- **Tools > Generate Netlist** (`.net` or `.xml`)\n    \n- Inspect key nets like `PWM_CH1`, `TRIG_1`, `VREG_5V`, `AUDIO_ENV`\n    \n- Verify all components are associated with a **footprint** (e.g., `Conn_01x03_Male` for servo headers, `LDO_SOT223`, etc.)\n    \n\n#### Key validation points:\n\n- All pins show up with expected connections\n    \n- Each output net (e.g. PWM) connects to exactly one output (MCU) and one or more inputs (servo headers)\n    \n- All power and GND nets are continuous\n    \n\n---\n\n### üßØ 5. **Common Errors to Watch For**\n\n- Duplicate net names with different voltages (e.g. `VCC` used for 3.3V and 5V)\n    \n- Floating analog inputs (add pulldowns or bias)\n    \n- Unassigned component footprints (blocks layout)\n    \n- Pin-swapped nets (e.g., TX/RX reversed)\n    \n- Incorrect net polarity (especially with PNP/NPN transistors or MOSFETs)\n    \n\n---\n\n### üìä Output: ERC Summary Report\n\nOnce validated, export an **ERC report** for documentation:\n\n#### ‚úÖ Sample Pass Report:\n\n```plaintext\nERC Check - Passed\n---------------------\n‚úî All power pins have valid connections\n‚úî No unconnected inputs or outputs\n‚úî No conflicting drivers on nets\n‚úî All global labels properly resolved\n‚úî Netlist generated with 0 warnings\n```\n\n---\n\n### üß© Next Steps\n\nWould you like me to:\n\n- Generate a sample `.ERC` or `.xml` **netlist file**?\n    \n- Create a **checklist template** for Obsidian or Git for versioned ERC runs?\n    \n- Output a **BOM and footprint list** to validate layout readiness?\n    \n\nLet me know what format or ECAD software you‚Äôre using and I can tailor the outputs accordingly.","x":3040,"y":1700,"width":1120,"height":3060},
		{"id":"fb4d446e23b574f5","x":4240,"y":1700,"width":1200,"height":4860,"type":"text","text":"# Task CD-T04 ‚Äì Generate and Verify PCB \n\nTransforming your validated schematic into a **PCB layout** for the puppet servo control system involves the following comprehensive workflow. This guide assumes you‚Äôre using **KiCad**, **Eagle**, or a similar EDA tool, and focuses on performance, reliability, and mechanical fit for puppetry integration.\n\n---\n\n## üß± Step-by-Step: PCB Layout for Puppet Servo Controller\n\n### üó∫Ô∏è 1. **Define Board Dimensions and Shape**\n\n- Choose mechanical format based on puppet housing constraints:\n    \n    - üìè Typical size: ~80mm √ó 50mm for compact control boards\n        \n    - üìê Mounting holes: 3.2mm diameter spaced to fit brackets/enclosures\n        \n- Import custom shape (DXF) if mounting inside curved or stylized puppet chassis\n    \n- Define board outline in **Edge.Cuts** layer\n    \n\n---\n\n### üîå 2. **Place Key Components (Top Layer)**\n\nOrganize by signal flow and ease of access:\n\n|Zone|Components|\n|---|---|\n|**Power In**|DC Jack / JST connector, TVS, Fuse, Regulator|\n|**MCU Zone**|MCU, reset button, oscillator, programming header|\n|**Servo Bank**|3-pin headers grouped in a row or column: Signal + VREG_5V + GND|\n|**Triggers**|Sensor inputs or buttons along board edge for wiring access|\n|**Audio Input**|Line-in jack or module mount, envelope follower circuit nearby|\n\nüîß **Tips**:\n\n- Group similar signal paths together\n    \n- Orient all polarized parts (caps, diodes) consistently\n    \n- Keep programming/debug headers on edge for easy access\n    \n\n---\n\n### üîÅ 3. **Route Power Traces First**\n\n- Use **thick traces** for power lines:\n    \n    - `VREG_5V` ‚Üí Servo bank: **‚â•1.0mm**\n        \n    - `VCC_MCU` (logic): **0.4mm**\n        \n- Add **ferrite bead or resistor** between analog/digital power domains if needed\n    \n- Use **wide pours** or **copper zones** for `GND` plane (Top & Bottom layer)\n    \n- Verify **return paths** for high-current PWM loads (important for servo noise)\n    \n\n---\n\n### üéöÔ∏è 4. **Signal Trace Routing**\n\n#### MCU to Servo PWM:\n\n- Keep short, direct traces from MCU to headers\n    \n- Add 33‚Äì100Œ© series resistors near MCU if servos cause EMI\n    \n\n#### Audio Signal:\n\n- Keep analog traces away from switching power or servo signals\n    \n- Use ground shielding (guard traces) around `AUDIO_ENV`\n    \n\n#### Trigger Inputs:\n\n- Pull-down resistors placed near input header\n    \n- Route clean digital signals away from PWM lines\n    \n\n---\n\n### üìê 5. **Apply Design Rules & Constraints**\n\n**Minimum Clearances:**\n\n- Signal spacing: ‚â•0.2mm\n    \n- Trace width: 0.25mm (signal), 1.0mm+ (power)\n    \n\n**Mechanical Check:**\n\n- Check edge component spacing\n    \n- Confirm header heights fit puppet enclosure\n    \n- Verify no overhanging components (e.g. USB, audio jack)\n    \n\n**Signal Integrity:**\n\n- Avoid sharp 90¬∞ corners (use 45¬∞ or curved)\n    \n- Keep trace length equal if synchrony matters (e.g. for I2C or SPI buses)\n    \n- Star-ground layout for separating logic vs servo power return\n    \n\n---\n\n### üîç 6. **Run DRC (Design Rule Check)**\n\n- Ensure **no unconnected pads**\n    \n- Validate **clearances**, **track widths**, **via sizes**\n    \n- Use **KiCad‚Äôs DRC** or **Eagle‚Äôs ERC/DRC panel**\n    \n\n---\n\n### üì§ 7. **Prepare for Fabrication**\n\n#### Required Output Files (Gerber & Fab):\n\n- Top/Bottom Copper (GTL/GBL)\n    \n- Top/Bottom Soldermask (GTS/GBS)\n    \n- Top/Bottom Silkscreen (GTO/GBO)\n    \n- Board Outline (GKO)\n    \n- Drill file (TXT or EXCELLON)\n    \n\n#### Optional:\n\n- 3D STEP model for mechanical fitting\n    \n- Interactive BOM (KiCad plugin) for sourcing\n    \n\n---\n\n### üì¶ Final Deliverables Checklist\n\n|File|Purpose|\n|---|---|\n|`control_board.kicad_pcb`|Full PCB design|\n|`gerbers/` folder|Manufacturer-ready files|\n|`bom.csv`|Component sourcing|\n|`3d_model.step`|Puppet fit confirmation|\n|`pdf/schematic.pdf`|Reference document|\n|`fab_notes.txt`|Any assembly/test instructions|\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to:\n\n- Create a **KiCad PCB layout file** from your schematic?\n    \n- Generate a **3D board mockup** inside a puppet enclosure?\n    \n- Provide **trace width calculations** for specific servo current loads?\n    \n\nLet me know your preferred board size or mounting constraints, and I can generate layout templates or actual project files."},
